Clipping Data

Clipping the population data to the India boundaries and then masked and plotted to check it worked correctly.

#2010 data
pop_count_2010_India <- crop(pop_count_2010, extent(India_boundaries))
pop_count_2010_India_mask <- mask(pop_count_2010_India, India_boundaries)
plot(pop_count_2010_India_mask)
# 2020 data 
pop_count_2020_India <- crop(pop_count_2020, extent(India_boundaries))
pop_count_2020_India_mask <- mask(pop_count_2020_India, India_boundaries)
plot(pop_count_2020_India_mask)

Zonal Statistics for 2020 data to work out density

To work out the population density the 2020 population count for India was extracted, the area of each boundary and the population density was calculated and plotted for Map 1.

#working out area of each region 
India_boundaries$area_km2 <- st_area(India_boundaries) / 10^6
# Calculate population density (people per square kilometer)
India_boundaries$density_2020 <- India_boundaries$pop_count_2020_India_mask / India_boundaries$area_km2
India_boundaries$density_2020 <- as.numeric(India_boundaries$density_2020)
library(units)

# Ensure that areas are in square kilometers
India_boundaries$area_km2 <- set_units(India_boundaries$area_km2, "km^2")

Categorical Change in Indiaâs population

The 2010 population count was then extracted, and the difference between 2010 and 2020 was calculated, then categorised into quantile classifications and plotted for Map 2

#finding pop difference between rasters
India_boundaries$pop_difference <- India_boundaries$pop_count_2020_India_mask - India_boundaries$pop_count_2010_India_mask
#calculating summary statistics
summary_stats <- summary(India_boundaries$pop_difference)
summary_stats
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
 -97054  101317  225461  321632  425766 3924099 
#looking at the distribution of my data on a histogram 
ggplot(India_boundaries, aes(x = pop_difference)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, fill = "blue", color = "black", alpha = 0.7) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Population Change", y = "Frequency", title = "Distribution of Population Change")
#reclassifying data using quantiles 
quantile_breaks <- classIntervals(India_boundaries$pop_difference, n = 4, style = "quantile")
India_boundaries$category <- cut(
  India_boundaries$pop_difference,
  breaks = quantile_breaks$brks,
  labels = c("Decline", "Neutral", "Growth", "High Growth")  # Customize labels as needed
)

Map 2

# Create the ggplot2 map
ggplot(data = India_boundaries) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = category), color = "black", size = 0.1) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c("Decline" = "red", "Neutral" = "orange", "Growth" = "lightgreen", "High Growth" = "darkgreen"),
    name = "Population Change", 
    na.translate= FALSE
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Population Change in India (2010 - 2020)",
    fill = "Change Category"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 12),
    legend.position = "right",
    legend.title = element_text(size = 10),
    legend.text = element_text(size = 8)
  ) +
  # Add scale bar
  annotation_scale(location = "bl", width_hint = 0.2, text_cex = 0.8) + 
  annotation_north_arrow(
    location = "br",
    which_north = "true",
    pad_x = unit(0.5, "cm"), pad_y = unit(0.5, "cm"),
    style = north_arrow_fancy_orienteering, height = unit(1, "cm"), 
    width = unit(1, "cm")
  )

Questions

  1. Each pixel is associated with the continuous variable of population count for a geographic location - India - within the raster grid; each cell has a single value and divides into pixels. The population count pixels are useful in showing the spatial trends and differences between each of Indiaâs regions . In map 2, the pixels continuous values where reclassified into categorical variables based on whether they were classed as showing decline, neutral, growth or high growth using quantiles. This allowed a visualisation of the trends at a regional level to be created for analysis.

  2. I am using a WGS84 CRS for both my population counts and India boundaries as it accurately preserves the earthâs shape as an ellipsoid model (not just a sphere) shown through the co-ordinates. Maintaining the same CRS is key in producing a consistent reference for Indiaâs population data and features whilst also ensuring that maps produced are aligned and not distorted.

  3. Map 1 highlights that within India there is a variety in density depending on the region, shown through the colour gradient of the blue to yellow scale, with yellow indicating the densest areas. The region on the northern border generally show low levels of population density whereas the region of Uttar Pradesh in the northeast displays some of the highest density values which can be accredited to the size of the region. Furthermore, the densest areas- shown by yellow colour- can be attributed to heavily urbanised areas such as Delhi and Mumbai where there is more opportunities for those living in India thus forming urban clustering. These valuable insights allow for future action by urban planners and governmental organisations to evaluate urban planning and policies.

  4. For map 2 I chose to categorically divide my data based on the initial exploration of summary statistics and histogram distribution. As India is a large area and currently has the highest population in the world it made sense to split it based on what is âhigh growthâ relative to the countries size and population count through a context-sensitive representation. Quantiles were chosen as the histogram displayed a positive skew; insuring the few extreme values wouldnât affect the interpretation of the categorization and balanced grouping could be created. The discrete groups: Decline, Neutral, Growth, High Growth where then able to be created and correctly convey the population change in India from 2010 to 2020. This ensured that the map conveyed that the areas of âhigh growthâ were in the context of the total population of India and the same with areas of decline. Map 2 revealed high growth in the same areas of high population density from map 1, and population decline in the low-density areas. This allows a connection to be made between population density and population counts from 2010 to 2020.
